00:13:56,669 --> 00:14:02,075
Today, I'm seeking $100,000 in
exchange for 20% of my company.

00:14:02,075 --> 00:14:03,743
As a social enterprise,

00:14:03,743 --> 00:14:06,746
iReTron is an online,
recommerce business

00:14:06,746 --> 00:14:10,016
that buys used
or unwanted electronics.

00:14:10,016 --> 00:14:12,719
Not only do we offer
the highest price on the market,

00:14:12,719 --> 00:14:15,088
but we are also
the greenest place for you

00:14:15,088 --> 00:14:17,490
to get rid of your cellphones,
calculators,

00:14:17,490 --> 00:14:19,092
MP3 players, and more.

00:14:19,092 --> 00:14:22,228
Now, sharks,
I know you guys always want

00:14:22,228 --> 00:14:24,931
the biggest, baddest, newest,
smartest smartphones

00:14:24,931 --> 00:14:26,366
there is to offer.

00:14:26,366 --> 00:14:29,102
However, not everyone
is that case.

00:14:29,102 --> 00:14:32,605
In fact me, myself, I don't
even want the newest model.

00:14:32,605 --> 00:14:36,342
And thus, iReTron caters to them
by providing older phones

00:14:36,342 --> 00:14:38,544
that still have years of life
left in them

00:14:38,544 --> 00:14:41,514
to people who can't pay the
full price for their technology.

00:14:41,514 --> 00:14:46,119
The best part is it's as easy
as, one, go on our website

00:14:46,119 --> 00:14:48,154
and receive an instant quote,

00:14:48,154 --> 00:14:51,624
and number two, ship us
your product free of charge.

00:14:51,624 --> 00:14:55,728
And finally, 3, get paid
in less than 48 hours.

00:14:55,728 --> 00:14:58,631
It's green for the world.
It's green for your wallet.

00:14:58,631 --> 00:15:02,068
What do you say, sharks?
Time for you to retron.

00:15:02,068 --> 00:15:04,370
Walk me
through an example.

00:15:04,370 --> 00:15:07,740
I sell you my old phone.
Right.

00:15:07,740 --> 00:15:09,008
Do you fix it up then

00:15:09,008 --> 00:15:11,177
and try to sell it
to somebody else?

00:15:11,177 --> 00:15:12,779
We'll inspect it
within 48 hours,

00:15:12,779 --> 00:15:14,013
then we'll send you a check.

00:15:14,013 --> 00:15:15,415
Okay.
So, your part is done.

00:15:15,415 --> 00:15:18,651
Do you have a guaranteed buyer
on your end?

00:15:18,651 --> 00:15:19,886
Yes.
And that's been proven

00:15:19,886 --> 00:15:21,487
because we've been running this
for two years,

00:15:21,487 --> 00:15:23,189
and we have zero inventory,

00:15:23,189 --> 00:15:25,458
meaning that it never
gets stuck.

00:15:25,458 --> 00:15:27,293
All right, selling it
is so much easier

00:15:27,293 --> 00:15:28,928
than actually getting
the product,

00:15:28,928 --> 00:15:30,029
and that's what we need
to work on.

00:15:30,029 --> 00:15:31,431
We need to market

00:15:31,431 --> 00:15:33,633
because I haven't spent any
money yet on advertisements.

00:15:33,633 --> 00:15:35,034
Jason,
what makes you different

00:15:35,034 --> 00:15:36,569
from the other 90 guys
doing this?

00:15:36,569 --> 00:15:38,104
Doing the exact same thing.

00:15:38,104 --> 00:15:39,572
LI: Right.

00:15:39,572 --> 00:15:41,674
Um, so, yes, I am aware that
we do have a lot of competition,

00:15:41,674 --> 00:15:43,576
but the one thing
that separates us

00:15:43,576 --> 00:15:45,411
is that
we're a social enterprise.

00:15:45,411 --> 00:15:46,913
If you look at our website,

00:15:46,913 --> 00:15:49,182
we accept over 5,000
different products,

00:15:49,182 --> 00:15:51,818
including products
that have literally no value

00:15:51,818 --> 00:15:54,420
because, number one,
it's environmentally friendly,

00:15:54,420 --> 00:15:57,089
and, number two, it's a simple
way of customer acquisition.

00:15:57,089 --> 00:15:58,558
So, you're basically
telling me

00:15:58,558 --> 00:16:00,326
you're making less for me
as an investor

00:16:00,326 --> 00:16:02,762
because you're buying stuff
that nobody wants,

00:16:02,762 --> 00:16:04,130
so that costs me.

00:16:04,130 --> 00:16:06,632
You're paying higher prices,
which kills my margins.

00:16:06,632 --> 00:16:09,368
Everybody's telling me they're
green because that's for free.

00:16:09,368 --> 00:16:10,870
Anybody can say that.
Mm-hmm.

00:16:10,870 --> 00:16:12,905
But there's so much competition.

00:16:12,905 --> 00:16:16,209
In fact, if you Google this,
there's so many pages,

00:16:16,209 --> 00:16:18,110
you'll die of old age
getting to the last.

00:16:18,110 --> 00:16:20,913
But if you Google us right now,
if you search, "sell my Kindle,"

00:16:20,913 --> 00:16:22,348
we're actually on the first page
of Google.

00:16:22,348 --> 00:16:24,750
All right, Jason.
Let's forget what Kevin says.

00:16:24,750 --> 00:16:27,987
Let's see what the market says.
What are your sales?

00:16:27,987 --> 00:16:31,090
So, in the past 12 months,
we made $40,000.

00:16:31,090 --> 00:16:33,326
And I don't want you guys

00:16:33,326 --> 00:16:35,528
to get caught up in the numbers
because --
Why not?

00:16:35,528 --> 00:16:37,263
Because you have to look
at our growth rate first.

00:16:37,263 --> 00:16:38,564
Our first --

00:16:38,564 --> 00:16:42,568
$40,000 in this industry
is an absolute-nothing burger.

00:16:42,568 --> 00:16:46,372
On that $40,000 that you made
in profit, how much --

00:16:46,372 --> 00:16:47,840
LI: $10,000.

00:16:47,840 --> 00:16:49,909
So, we have about
a 25% net-profit margin.

00:16:49,909 --> 00:16:51,611
Jason,
do you do this full-time?

00:16:51,611 --> 00:16:53,646
No. I'm 16 years old.
I'm a senior in high --

00:16:53,646 --> 00:16:54,814
Oh, you're only 16?
You're 16?

00:16:54,814 --> 00:16:56,182
Wow.
Yeah.

00:16:56,182 --> 00:16:57,717
Look at the size of you.
Wow. I thought
you were in college.

00:16:57,717 --> 00:16:58,751
I thought you were,
like, 25.

00:16:58,751 --> 00:17:00,086
Oh, no, no, no.
CUBAN: Freshman.

00:17:00,086 --> 00:17:01,420
Oh, yeah.
You look very mature.

00:17:01,420 --> 00:17:02,522
LI: Thank you.
So, I have a question.

00:17:02,522 --> 00:17:03,756
Now we have to be
nicer to you.

00:17:03,756 --> 00:17:07,627
You're obviously very savvy.
You know what's out there.

00:17:07,627 --> 00:17:10,396
What do you think you have
to offer that's better?

00:17:10,396 --> 00:17:13,399
Um, well, the one thing
that separates us --

00:17:13,399 --> 00:17:16,769
you know, we're not always,
you know, 100% profit-driven.

00:17:16,769 --> 00:17:18,905
We care about social,
environment,

00:17:18,905 --> 00:17:20,273
and profit all equally.

00:17:20,273 --> 00:17:21,741
Jason, what drives you?

00:17:21,741 --> 00:17:23,175
Is it
the social responsibility,

00:17:23,175 --> 00:17:25,077
or are you -- are you trying
to build a business?

00:17:25,077 --> 00:17:27,580
I think there was --
there's a lot of things.

00:17:27,580 --> 00:17:30,917
Um, I immigrated to America
when I was 6 years old.

00:17:30,917 --> 00:17:32,985
Where'd you come from?
China.

00:17:32,985 --> 00:17:34,554
I always wanted to be
independent,

00:17:34,554 --> 00:17:36,088
and I always wanted
to contribute

00:17:36,088 --> 00:17:37,456
rather than to take for myself.

00:17:37,456 --> 00:17:40,326
