and took majority ownership

00:38:55,333 --> 00:38:59,771
and took it over
and let him retain equity?

00:38:59,771 --> 00:39:01,573
Are you nuts?
All right, what amount?

00:39:01,573 --> 00:39:06,878
What if we gave them 300k
for 60%?

00:39:06,878 --> 00:39:08,913
And I've never, ever --
in every deal

00:39:08,913 --> 00:39:10,615
I've ever done
on "Shark Tank"

00:39:10,615 --> 00:39:12,951
even offered
to take a majority.

00:39:12,951 --> 00:39:14,319
To me,
that's always a negative.

00:39:14,319 --> 00:39:16,020
But in this --
So, why is this different?

00:39:16,020 --> 00:39:18,389
This is different because
you're creating a category,

00:39:18,389 --> 00:39:20,525
and you need pros
who are going to come in

00:39:20,525 --> 00:39:21,626
and fight the battle.

00:39:21,626 --> 00:39:23,595
We take that 300k.

00:39:23,595 --> 00:39:26,231
That way, you can take the 150k,
pay back your parents.

00:39:26,231 --> 00:39:28,700
Mark, why don't you just stick
your head in that beehive?

00:39:28,700 --> 00:39:29,767
It's easier.

00:39:29,767 --> 00:39:30,802
Yeah.
[laughs]

00:39:30,802 --> 00:39:32,770
You know, Kevin,
that's the thing.

00:39:32,770 --> 00:39:34,606
That's the difference
between us, Kevin.

00:39:34,606 --> 00:39:37,108
I see an idea,
I see an opportunity,

00:39:37,108 --> 00:39:40,111
and I can see the endgame
and how it can be enormous.

00:39:40,111 --> 00:39:42,146
HERJAVEC: Mark,
it's an interesting angle,

00:39:42,146 --> 00:39:44,749
but I don't think your pricing
enough of the risk at 60%.

00:39:46,251 --> 00:39:48,853
Let's do the $300,000
for 75%.

00:39:50,421 --> 00:39:51,789
Now who's the vampire?

00:39:53,057 --> 00:39:54,392
This could be
something big.

00:39:54,392 --> 00:39:57,929
$300,000 for 75%.

00:39:57,929 --> 00:40:00,865
$150,000 each
from Mark and I.

00:40:00,865 --> 00:40:02,734
[sighs]

00:40:02,734 --> 00:40:04,168
There's no way
you would consider

00:40:04,168 --> 00:40:05,670
anything less
than majority share?

00:40:05,670 --> 00:40:07,739
T-the thing about it is

00:40:07,739 --> 00:40:10,875
we want the ability to just
take this and run with it.

00:40:10,875 --> 00:40:11,910
I get that.

00:40:11,910 --> 00:40:13,278
One of the challenges
in "Shark Tank"

00:40:13,278 --> 00:40:14,545
is we invest in companies --

00:40:14,545 --> 00:40:16,080
at least, that I've learned
over the years,

00:40:16,080 --> 00:40:17,715
is when it's family-run,

00:40:17,715 --> 00:40:20,118
there's a lot
of unique dynamics.

00:40:20,118 --> 00:40:23,421
And it's very difficult
to just say, "Go, go, go,"

00:40:23,421 --> 00:40:27,125
which is what you want when
you've just invested $150,000

00:40:27,125 --> 00:40:29,193
and you see
the opportunity.

00:40:29,193 --> 00:40:31,029
You're still a kid, but
let me tell you something.

00:40:31,029 --> 00:40:33,965
When we get this serious
about it, money sees no age.

00:40:33,965 --> 00:40:37,135
It's real money.
It's real serious.

00:40:37,135 --> 00:40:38,903
Henry, it's your business,
so this is a serious thing.

00:40:38,903 --> 00:40:40,004
It's a big thing.

00:40:40,004 --> 00:40:41,539
I-if you want to make
a phone call --

00:40:41,539 --> 00:40:43,574
MILLER:
I'm not gonna consult my parents

00:40:43,574 --> 00:40:45,743
because they told me,
"This is your company.

00:40:45,743 --> 00:40:48,146
"Even though it's our money,
you started this thing.

00:40:48,146 --> 00:40:49,314
This is your baby."

00:40:49,314 --> 00:40:51,449
Look, Henry, I don't want
to sugar-coat this

00:40:51,449 --> 00:40:53,384
and try to talk you
into anything.

00:40:53,384 --> 00:40:55,720
I want to be brutally honest
on this, right?

00:40:55,720 --> 00:40:57,822
Because it's
a new category --

00:40:57,822 --> 00:40:59,757
